text: I feel kind of sick....this film is based on a brilliant, NY Times booklist, million seller book from 1979. In the book, David is mentally ill and abnormally obsessed with primarily the girl but also her family.  The author of the book is Scott Spencer (more than one movie is out there based on his works; all due to his incredible writing, look it up).  It's a long, gut-wrenching novel that will tear your heart out of your ass.   Read it. The original 1981 movie at least tried to stick with the original premise, so see that instead.  This seems awful, just from the trailer.

text: The original movie of ENDLESS LOVE captivated millions of viewers around the world. The original movie did focus on the passion and intense love of JADE (BROOKE SHIELDS and DAVID (MARTIN HEWITT). the novel is an account of DAVID'S love for JADE. The movie also included the arson that david did and was sent to MENTAL FACILITY instead of jail. He was released but he did see the family and Jade which he should not done as he was in probation. Jades father got hit by a car. not DAVIDS FAULT. so he was sent back to the mental facility. few years after. Jade went to visit him as it is ENDLESS LOVE for both of them- just as Jades mother told her she deserve anything. so Jade followed her heart against all odds. Great movie in 1981. the remake did not follow the story but used JADE and DAVID character the rest was not in the novel and the 1981 movie. ENDLESS LOVE in 1981 was very touching and heartbreaking.

text: Again, I post this; I feel kind of sick....this film is based on a brilliant, NY Times booklist, million seller book from 1979. In the book, David is mentally ill and abnormally obsessed with primarily the girl but also her family.  The author of the book is Scott Spencer (more than one movie is out there based on his works; all due to his incredible writing, look it up).  It's a long, gut-wrenching novel that will tear your heart out of your ass.   Read it. The original 1981 movie at least tried to stick with the original premise, so see that instead.  This seems awful, just from the trailer.  Girls, if you want a great romance movie, go back in time to movies made years ago...the ones they are making today aren't that great.  Try Romeo and Juliet from 1968.....for a start.

text: This was probably the cheesiest, most cliche movie I've ever seen. And as much as I cringed, and had to pause and look away from the screen because it was so unbearably romantic and unrealistic and rushed, it was beautiful. The scene of the fire... I was in tears. I was uncontrollably sobbing and it was so incredible for this movie to have done this to me, because the entire time prior I was whispering to myself, "this is so mushy, it makes me sick." It's cheesey- too cheesey- but nevertheless a movie worth watching. That fire scene was heart wrenching, and I couldn't have loved it more.
